** Alain de Botton on Love=2C Vulnerability=2C and the Psychological Parad=
ox of the Sulk (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/27/alain-de-botton-t=
he-course-of-love/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1501134256/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946=
e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CNothing awakens us to the reality of life so much as a true love=
=2C=E2=80=9D Vincent van Gogh wrote to his brother (https://www.brainpicki=
ngs.org/2016/04/20/van-gogh-heartbreak/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) . =E2=80=9CWhy is love rich beyond all other possible human experien=
ces and a sweet burden to those seized in its grasp?=E2=80=9D philosopher=
 Martin Heidegger asked in his electrifying love letters to Hannah Arendt=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/25/hannah-arendt-martin-heidegger-=
love-letters/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CBecause w=
e become what we love and yet remain ourselves.=E2=80=9D Still=2C nearly e=
very anguishing aspect of love arises from the inescapable tension between=
 this longing for transformative awakening and the sleepwalking selfhood o=
f our habitual patterns. True as it may be that frustration is a prerequis=
ite for satisfaction in romance (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/05/=
adam-phillips-missing-out-frustration-love/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) =2C how are we to reconcile the sundering frustration of these p=
olar pulls?

The multiple sharp-edged facets of this question are what Alain de Botton=
 explores in The Course of Love (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/15=
01134256/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (=
http://www.worldcat.org/title/course-of-love-a-novel/oclc/918616385&refere=
r=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 a me=
ditation on the beautiful=2C tragic tendernesses and fragilities of the hu=
man heart=2C at once unnerving and assuring in its psychological insightfu=
lness. At its heart is a lamentation of =E2=80=94 or=2C perhaps=2C an admo=
nition against =E2=80=94 how the classic Romantic model has sold us on a n=
umber of self-defeating beliefs about the most essential and nuanced exper=
iences of human life: love=2C infatuation=2C marriage=2C sex=2C children=
=2C infidelity=2C trust.

Alain de Botton

A sequel of sorts to his 1993 novel On Love (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2011/04/18/5-must-read-books-on-love/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) =2C the book is bold bending of form that fuses fiction and De Botton=
=E2=80=99s supreme forte (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/06/26/proust-=
school-of-life-art/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the essay=
 =E2=80=94 twined with the narrative thread of the romance between the two=
 protagonists are astute observations at the meeting point of psychology a=
nd philosophy=2C spinning out from the particular problems of the couple t=
o unravel broader insight into the universal complexities of the human hea=
rt.

In fact=2C as the book progresses=2C one gets the distinct and surprisingl=
y pleasurable sense that De Botton has sculpted the love story around the=
 robust armature of these philosophical meditations; that the essay is the=
 raison d=E2=80=99=C3=AAtre for the fiction.

In one of these contemplative interstitials=2C De Botton examines the para=
doxical psychology of one of the most common and most puzzling phenomena b=
etween lovers: sulking. He writes:

At the heart of a sulk lies a confusing mixture of intense anger and an eq=
ually intense desire not to communicate what one is angry about. The sulke=
r both desperately needs the other person to understand and yet remains ut=
terly committed to doing nothing to help them do so. The very need to expl=
ain forms the kernel of the insult: if the partner requires an explanation=
=2C he or she is clearly not worthy of one. We should add: it is a privile=
ge to be the recipient of a sulk; it means the other person respects and t=
rusts us enough to think we should understand their unspoken hurt. It is o=
ne of the odder gifts of love.

Sulking=2C De Botton suggests=2C stems from a form of magical thinking =E2=
=80=94 the belief=2C endearing in its origin but deleterious in its effect=
=2C that an impossibility is possible:

Sulking pays homage to a beautiful=2C dangerous ideal that can be traced b=
ack to our earliest childhoods: the promise of wordless understanding. In=
 the womb=2C we never had to explain. Our every requirement was catered to=
=2E The right sort of comfort simply happened. Some of this idyll continued=
 in our first years. We didn=E2=80=99t have to make our every requirement=
 known: large=2C kind people guessed for us. They saw past our tears=2C ou=
r inarticulacy=2C our confusions: they found the explanations for discomfo=
rts which we lacked the ability to verbalize.

That may be why=2C in relationships=2C even the most eloquent among us may=
 instinctively prefer not to spell things out when our partners are at ris=
k of failing to read us properly. Only wordless and accurate mind reading=
 can feel like a true sign that our partner is someone to be trusted; only=
 when we don=E2=80=99t have to explain can we feel certain that we are gen=
uinely understood.

But rather than bemoaning the sulk as a fatal flaw of a relationship=2C De=
 Botton wrests from it evidence of the most hopeful and generous capacity=
 of the human heart:

We would ideally remain able to laugh=2C in the gentlest way=2C when we ar=
e made the special target of a sulker=E2=80=99s fury. We would recognize t=
he touching paradox. The sulker may be six foot one and holding down adult=
 employment=2C but the real message is poignantly retrogressive: =E2=80=9C=
Deep inside=2C I remain an infant=2C and right now I need you to be my par=
ent. I need you correctly to guess what is truly ailing me=2C as people di=
d when I was a baby=2C when my ideas of love were first formed.=E2=80=9D

We do our sulking lovers the greatest possible favor when we are able to r=
egard their tantrums as we would those of an infant. We are so alive to th=
e idea that it=E2=80=99s patronizing to be thought of as younger than we a=
re; we forget that it is also=2C at times=2C the greatest privilege for so=
meone to look beyond our adult self in order to engage with =E2=80=94 and=
 forgive =E2=80=94 the disappointed=2C furious=2C inarticulate child withi=
n.

Art by Isol from Daytime Visions (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/25=
/daytime-visions-isol/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Half a century after Iris Murdoch consoled a heartbroken friend (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2016/02/24/iris-murdoch-causality-chance-love/?mc_cid=
=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by reminding her that =E2=80=9Clove is b=
etter than no love=2C though it can hurt so much=2C=E2=80=9D De Botton rev=
isits another facet of the same bewildering dynamic in a section on the in=
terplay between trust and blame:

The most superficially irrational=2C immature=2C lamentable=2C but nonethe=
less common of all the presumptions of love is that the person to whom we=
 have pledged ourselves is not just the center of our emotional existence=
 but is also=2C as a result =E2=80=94 and yet in a very strange=2C objecti=
vely insane and profoundly unjust way =E2=80=94 responsible for everything=
 that happens to us=2C for good or ill. Therein lies the peculiar and sick=
 privilege of love.

Toward the end of the book=2C De Botton follows this paradoxical privilege=
 to its equally paradoxical conclusion:

Maturity begins with the capacity to sense and=2C in good time and without=
 defensiveness=2C admit to our own craziness. If we are not regularly deep=
ly embarrassed by who we are=2C the journey to self-knowledge hasn=E2=80=
=99t begun.

The Course of Love (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1501134256/bpnl=
-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is an immensely perceptive and=
 pleasurable read in its totality. Complement it with philosopher Erich Fr=
omm on what is keeping us from mastering the art of loving (https://www.br=
ainpickings.org/2015/10/29/the-art-of-loving-erich-fromm/?mc_cid=3D834d946=
e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C sociologist Eva Illouz on why love hurts (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/22/why-love-hurts-eva-illouz/?mc_cid=3D8=
34d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and Anna Dostoyevsky on the secret to a=
 happy marriage (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/02/15/anna-dostoyevsky=
-reminiscences-marriage/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then=
 revisit De Botton on the seven psychological functions of art (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2013/10/25/art-as-therapy-alain-de-botton-john-armstro=
ng/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and what philosophy is for (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/24/what-is-philosophy-for-alain-de-bot=
ton/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

For more of his largehearted wisdom on love and our human vulnerabilities=
=2C see his magnificent Design Matters (https://www.brainpickings.org/tag/=
design-matters/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) conversation with=
 Debbie Millman:

https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/27/alain-de-botton-the-course-of-lov=
e/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

My view of human nature is that all of us are just holding it together in=
 various ways =E2=80=94 and that=E2=80=99s okay=2C and we just need to go=
 easy with one another=2C knowing that we=E2=80=99re all these incredibly=
 fragile beings.

Subscribe to Design Matters here (http://itunes.com/designmatters?mc_cid=
=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) for more invigorating conversations with=
 artists=2C writers=2C designers=2C and other creative thinkers.


