** Schopenhauer on What Makes a Genius and the Crucial Difference Between=
 Talent and Genius (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/29/schopenhauer-=
genius/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0486217620/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946=
e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CGenius gives birth=2C talent delivers=2C=E2=80=9D Jack Kerouac as=
serted in contemplating whether great artists are born or made (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2014/10/17/are-writers-born-or-made-jack-kerouac/?mc_c=
id=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CTalent is insignificant. I=
 know a lot of talented ruins=2C=E2=80=9D James Baldwin cautioned aspiring=
 writers as he considered the real building blocks of genius (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2016/02/08/james-baldwin-advice-on-writing/?mc_cid=3D834=
d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . More than a century earlier=2C Thoreau made=
 a vital distinction between an artisan=2C an artist=2C and a genius (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/03/thoreau-on-genius/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6=
f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

But perhaps the most useful and timelessly insightful take on the perennia=
l puzzlement over the difference between talent and genius came the year a=
fter Thoreau=E2=80=99s birth from the great German philosopher Arthur Scho=
penhauer (February 22=2C 1788=E2=80=93September 21=2C 1860) in his 1818 ma=
sterwork The World as Will and Representation (http://www.amazon.com/exec/=
obidos/ASIN/0486217612/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (pu=
blic library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/world-as-will-and-representati=
on/oclc/276339&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) ).

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0486217612/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946=
e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Schopenhauer=E2=80=99s central premise is that talent achieves what others=
 cannot achieve=2C whereas genius achieves what others cannot imagine. Thi=
s vision of a different order=2C he argues=2C is what sets geniuses apart=
 from mere mortals=2C and it arises from a superior capacity for contempla=
tion that leads the genius to transcend the smallness of the ego and enter=
 the infinite world of ideas. He writes:

Only through [such] pure contemplation =E2=80=A6 can Ideas be comprehende=
d; and the nature of genius consists in pre-eminent capacity for such cont=
emplation. Now=2C as this requires that a man* should entirely forget hims=
elf and the relations in which he stands=2C genius is simply the completes=
t objectivity=2C i.e.=2C the objective tendency of the mind=2C as opposed=
 to the subjective=2C which is directed to one=E2=80=99s own self =E2=80=
=94 in other words=2C to the will. Thus genius is the faculty of continuin=
g in the state of pure perception=2C of losing oneself in perception=2C an=
d of enlisting in this service the knowledge which originally existed only=
 for the service of the will; that is to say=2C genius is the power of lea=
ving one=E2=80=99s own interests=2C wishes=2C and aims entirely out of sig=
ht=2C thus of entirely renouncing one=E2=80=99s own personality for a time=
=2C so as to remain pure knowing subject=2C clear vision of the world; and=
 this not merely at moments=2C but for a sufficient length of time=2C and=
 with sufficient
consciousness=2C to enable one to reproduce by deliberate art what has thu=
s been apprehended.

But although a superior capacity to imagine is a centerpiece of genius=2C=
 Schopenhauer cautions against mistaking the imagination for the entirety=
 of genius:

Imagination has rightly been recognized as an essential element of genius;=
 it has sometimes even been regarded as identical with it; but this is a m=
istake. As the objects of genius are the eternal Ideas=2C the permanent=2C=
 essential forms of the world and all its phenomena=2C and as the knowledg=
e of the Idea is necessarily knowledge through perception=2C is not abstra=
ct=2C the knowledge of the genius would be limited to the Ideas of the obj=
ects actually present to his person=2C and dependent upon the chain of cir=
cumstances that brought these objects to him=2C if his imagination did not=
 extend his horizon far beyond the limits of his actual personal existence=
=2C and thus enable him to construct the whole out of the little that come=
s into his own actual apperception=2C and so to let almost all possible sc=
enes of life pass before him in his own consciousness=E2=80=A6 The imagina=
tion then extends the intellectual horizon of the man of genius beyond the=
 objects which actually present themselves to him=2C
both as regards quality and quantity. Therefore extraordinary strength of=
 imagination accompanies=2C and is indeed a necessary condition of genius.=
 But the converse does not hold=2C for strength of imagination does not in=
dicate genius; on the contrary=2C men who have no touch of genius may have=
 much imagination.

But the curse of the extraordinary=2C Schopenhauer suggests=2C is a certai=
n loneliness with which the person of genius walks through life=2C always=
 slightly apart from the ordinary world in being slightly above it:

The common mortal=2C that manufacture of Nature which she produces by the=
 thousand every day=2C is=2C as we have said=2C not capable=2C at least no=
t continuously so=2C of observation that in every sense is wholly disinter=
ested=2C as sensuous contemplation=2C strictly so called=2C is. He can tur=
n his attention to things only so far as they have some relation to his wi=
ll=2C however indirect it may be=E2=80=A6 The man of genius=2C on the othe=
r hand=2C whose excessive power of knowledge frees it at times from the se=
rvice of will=2C dwells on the consideration of life itself=2C strives to=
 comprehend the Idea of each thing=2C not its relations to other things; a=
nd in doing this he often forgets to consider his own path in life=2C and=
 therefore for the most part pursues it awkwardly enough. While to the ord=
inary man his faculty of knowledge is a lamp to lighten his path=2C to the=
 man of genius it is the sun which reveals the world=E2=80=A6 The man in w=
hom genius lives and works is easily distinguished by his glance=2C which=
 is
both keen and steady=2C and bears the stamp of perception=2C of contemplat=
ion.

In the second volume (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0486217620/bp=
nl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of his treatise=2C Schopenha=
uer revisits the subject of talent versus genius through the lens of time=
 =E2=80=94 talent=2C he argues=2C speaks brilliantly to the moment and is=
 of the moment=2C while genius speaks of the eternal and to eternity. He w=
rites:

Mere men of talent always come at the right time; for=2C as they are rouse=
d by the spirit of their age and are called into being by its needs=2C the=
y are only just capable of satisfying them. They therefore go hand in hand=
 with the advancing culture of their contemporaries=2C or with the gradual=
 advancement of a special science; for this they reap reward and approbati=
on. But to the next generation their works are no longer enjoyable; they m=
ust be replaced by others; and these do not fail to appear.

The genius=2C on the other hand=2C lights on his age like a comet into the=
 paths of the planets=2C to whose well-regulated and comprehensible arrang=
ement its wholly eccentric course is foreign. Accordingly=2C he cannot go=
 hand in hand with the regular course of the culture of the times as found=
; on the contrary=2C he casts his works far out on to the path in front (j=
ust as the emperor=2C giving himself up to death=2C flings his spear among=
 the enemy)=2C on which time has first to overtake them=E2=80=A6 Talent is=
 able to achieve what is beyond other people=E2=80=99s capacity to achieve=
=2C yet not what is beyond their capacity of apprehension; therefore it at=
 once finds its appreciators. The achievement of genius=2C on the other ha=
nd=2C transcends not only others=E2=80=99 capacity of achievement=2C but a=
lso their capacity of apprehension; therefore they do not become immediate=
ly aware of it. Talent is like the marksman who hits a target which others=
 cannot reach; genius is like the marksman who hits a target =E2=80=A6 whi=
ch
others cannot even see.

The World as Will and Representation (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/AS=
IN/0486217620/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 on=
e of Oliver Sacks=E2=80=99s favorite books (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2016/02/11/oliver-sacks-reading-list/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) and the source of Schopenhauer=E2=80=99s abiding insight into the powe=
r of music (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/15/writers-on-music/?mc_=
cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 is an indispensable read in=
 its totality. Complement it with Schopenhauer on the intellectual rewards=
 of boredom (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/16/boredom/?mc_cid=3D83=
4d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit William James on the habit o=
f mind that sets geniuses apart (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/25/=
william-james-attention/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and mathe=
