** Artist Anne Truitt on Love=2C Loss=2C Regret=2C What Makes Marriage Wor=
k=2C and the Syncopation of Grief and Gladness (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2016/07/01/anne-truitt-turn-regret-mourning-love/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0670811750/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946=
e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Perhaps because she was trained as a psychologist=2C artist Anne Truitt (M=
arch 16=2C 1921=E2=80=93December 23=2C 2004) had a special attentiveness t=
o the inner life of the creative spirit and a great gift for articulating=
 that aliveness with lyrical nuance in her prolific diaries (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/tag/anne-truitt/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 . She wrote especially beautifully about the parallels between being an a=
rtist and being a parent (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/11/anne-tr=
uitt-daybook-artist-parenting/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=
=80=94 an insight forced upon her partly by circumstances as the demands o=
f the latter role swelled in intensity after she divorced her husband=2C t=
he journalist James Truitt=2C in 1969. She became the primary parent of th=
eir three children =E2=80=94 Alexandra (age 14)=2C Mary (age 11)=2C and Sa=
m (age 9) =E2=80=94 and then a single parent after James=E2=80=99s death i=
n 1981. All the while=2C Truitt remained an artist of remarkable disciplin=
e and integrity=2C continuing to create work that would render her one of=
 the most
significant=2C visionary=2C and influential sculptors of the twentieth cen=
tury.

Emanating from her distinctive sculptures=2C where vibrant colors possess=
 and are possessed by muted minimalist shapes=2C is a certain subtle dialo=
gue between gain and loss=2C between what is and what isn=E2=80=99t=2C or=
 perhaps what never was and never could be.

Anne Truitt in Tokyo=2C 1966

Nowhere is this syncopation of grief and gladness more resonant than in on=
e particular entry from the altogether magnificent Turn: The Journal of an=
 Artist (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0670811750/bpnl-20?mc_cid=
=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org=
/title/turn-the-journal-of-an-artist/oclc/13333324&referer=3Dbrief_results=
?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 the same volume that=
 gave us Truitt=E2=80=99s timeless wisdom on vulnerability=2C the price of=
 artistic integrity=2C and what sustains the creative spirit (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2016/01/21/anne-truitt-turn-art/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

Truitt writes in August of 1983=2C when her son was twenty:

I was in the kitchen the other day when Sam read me a line of Borges: =E2=
=80=9CYou can only lose what you have never had=2C=E2=80=9D and I have bee=
n thinking it over ever since. The truth is instantly recognizable; it mig=
ht almost be a platitude. But it came at me at an angle around a corner fr=
om his lair of books in Sam=E2=80=99s reflective voice=2C and touched a so=
re spot in my memory of his father.

For when I mourn=2C I do mourn what he and I never had: the lovely entire=
 confidence that comes only from innumerable mutual confidences entrusted=
 and examined. And woven by four hands=2C now trembling=2C now intent=2C o=
ver and under into a pattern that can surprise both husband and wife. I mi=
ss the rich doubling of experience that comes only from such confidence=2C=
 the nuances of refraction and reflection=2C nourished and enhanced and un=
derwritten by the sweet union of familiar bodies =E2=80=94 touch and smell=
=2C tidal.

Masaccio=2C Expulsion from the Garden of Eden

But the most piercing point of mourning=2C Truitt observes=2C is that of r=
egret =E2=80=94 the irremediable regret of having held back=2C of having l=
et the fearsome vulnerability of being hurt preclude the grand reward of b=
eing truly understood. She writes:

I mourn my failures to confide. I should have had more courage=2C dared=2C=
 risked rejection=2C even ejection =E2=80=94 naked=2C awkward=2C crouched=
 as Eve in Masaccio=E2=80=99s Expulsion from Paradise. =E2=80=9CShould=E2=
=80=9D is a dreadful auxiliary word=2C and worst when linked with =E2=80=
=9Chave=2C=E2=80=9D rendering an act one never thought of at a certain tim=
e=2C or thought of and decided not to do=2C as effective and inexorably ir=
revocable as a deed done.

I mourn what I did not know when I was married: the necessity for honesty=
 between people if mutuality is to bud out of a status quo into air it can=
 then fill with a new form. When I saw how one of the Australian gum trees=
=2C the angophora=2C thrust out new branches=2C I saw how a marriage could=
 work: a nub pushes out from a fork and as it grows into a branch (there a=
re wide-branched trees) the bark of the tree=E2=80=99s trunk spreads smoot=
hly over this rough=2C crude juncture so that it joins the other branches=
 seamlessly=2C enhances the whole tree=E2=80=99s amplitude. The bark is pu=
rple=2C tan-pink-violet. There is warmth in its seal.

This poetic image of growth through sealing and healing together reminded=
 me of Jane Hirshfield=E2=80=99s beautiful poem =E2=80=9CFor What Binds Us=
=2C=E2=80=9D included in her altogether sublime 1988 collection Of Gravity=
 & Angels (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0819511382/bpnl-20?mc_ci=
d=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.or=
g/title/of-gravity-angels/oclc/16468284&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D8=
34d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ):

FOR WHAT BINDS US

There are names for what binds us:
strong forces=2C weak forces.
Look around=2C you can see them:
the skin that forms in a half-empty cup=2C
nails rusting into the places they join=2C
joints dovetailed on their own weight.
The way things stay so solidly
wherever they=E2=80=99ve been set down =E2=80=94
and gravity=2C scientists say=2C is weak.

And see how the flesh grows back
across a wound=2C with a great vehemence=2C
more strong
than the simple=2C untested surface before.
There=E2=80=99s a name for it on horses=2C
when it comes back darker and raised: proud flesh=2C

as all flesh=2C
is proud of its wounds=2C wears them
as honors given out after battle=2C
small triumphs pinned to the chest =E2=80=94

And when two people have loved each other
see how it is like a
scar between their bodies=2C
stronger=2C darker=2C and proud;
how the black cord makes of them a single fabric
that nothing can tear or mend.

But as she continues her diaristic meditation=2C Truitt suggests that perh=
aps regret =E2=80=94 the regret of not having conjoined each other=E2=80=
=99s woundedness boldly enough in order to mend and grow together =E2=80=
=94 is the one thing that can tear a relationship=2C or the memory of a re=
lationship. She reflects on her gum tree epiphany:

I am saddened that I learned this truth so late=2C but the ironic fact is=
 that I only came to realize it because of what my children taught me whil=
e I was bringing them up alone. The staunchness of their affection and the=
 openness of their hearts slowly brought me to an emotional courage for wh=
ich I had simply never before had the security.

Anne Truitt with two of her three children and two of her eight grandchild=
ren. (Photograph: Mariana Cook=2C 1997)

Turn (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0670811750/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D8=
34d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is a revelatory and profoundly pleasurable r=
ead in its entirety. Complement this particular portion with Kathryn Schul=
z on the psychology of regret (https://www.brainpickings.org/2011/12/05/ka=
thryn-schulz-regret-ted/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Rilke=
 on how great losses bring us closer to ourselves (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2015/03/10/rilke-letters-to-a-young-poet-sadness/?mc_cid=3D834d946e=
6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Truitt on compassion and humility=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/09/12/anne-truitt-humility-compassion=
-righteousness/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the ideal dail=
