** Mapping the Heavens: How Cosmology Shaped Our Understanding of the Univ=
erse and the Strange Story of How the Term =E2=80=9CBlack Hole=E2=80=9D Wa=
s Born (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/27/mapping-the-heavens-natar=
ajan-black-holes/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0300204418/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946=
e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CWhen they gazed at the sky =E2=80=94 infinite=2C remote and exist=
ing quite apart from their puny lives =E2=80=94 people had a religious exp=
erience=2C=E2=80=9D historian Karen Armstrong wrote in examining our earli=
est myths (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/08/karen-armstrong-short-=
history-of-myth/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CThe sk=
y towered above them=2C inconceivably immense=2C inaccessible and eternal.=
 It was the very essence of transcendence and otherness.=E2=80=9D Our sens=
emaking instinct pounced on that transcendent otherness and we spent 4=2C0=
00 years mapping the skies (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/31/cosmi=
graphics-michael-benson/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . But whe=
re mythology seeks to contain that overwhelming immensity in a set of illu=
sory certitudes=2C science uses every new piece of knowledge as a key to a=
 door into an even vaster unknown. Trailblazing astronomer Maria Mitchell=
 captured this beautifully in her diary (https://www.brainpickings.org/201=
3/08/01/maria-mitchell-diaries/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) :=
 =E2=80=9CWe reach forth and strain every nerve=2C but we seize only
a bit of the curtain that hides the infinite from us.=E2=80=9D

It was only the last century or so=2C much thanks to Einstein=E2=80=99s se=
minal theory of relativity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/13/einst=
ein-maier-simon-nobrow/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C that w=
e have devised systematic ways of incrementally lifting the curtain. In Ma=
pping the Heavens: The Radical Scientific Ideas That Reveal the Cosmos (ht=
tp://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0300204418/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6=
f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/mappi=
ng-the-heavens-the-radical-scientific-ideas-that-reveal-the-cosmos/oclc/92=
3562187&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=
=2C Yale theoretical astrophysicist Priyamvada Natarajan explores how the=
 advent of modern cosmology and astrophysics has shaped our understanding=
 of the universe and our place in it. Natarajan uses the inquiries at the=
 center of her research =E2=80=94 illuminating how black holes (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2016/04/25/black-hole-blues-janna-levin-joseph-weber/?=
mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) form and mapping dark matter
(https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/11/28/dark-matter-and-the-dinosaurs-li=
sa-randall/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 as a lens th=
rough which to chronicle some of the most significant and disorienting dis=
coveries in science. Radiating from the history of these paradigm-shifting=
 breakthroughs is a larger meditation on how groundbreaking ideas are drea=
mt up=2C tested against reality=2C contested by the quintessential human r=
esistance to the fraying of the status quo=2C and finally woven into the f=
abric of our accepted understanding.

The Nebra Sky Disc (2000=E2=80=931600 B.C.)=2C excavated illegally in Germ=
any in 1999=2C is considered the oldest known visualization of celestial o=
bjects. Part of the Bronze Age =C3=9An=C3=AAtice culture=2C it depicts the=
 sun or the full moon=2C a lunar crescent=2C and stars in a hammered coppe=
r-and-gold plate.

Natarajan writes:

The journey to acceptance of an idea reveals many other facets of science=
 =E2=80=94 the emotional=2C psychological=2C personal=2C and social dimens=
ions that extend beyond the purely intellectual pursuit of knowledge.

[=E2=80=A6]

The scientific mind is honed during training to be nimble=2C and the pract=
ice of science tests this agility on a daily basis. This inoculates scient=
ists against disorienting shocks when a preponderance of new data and evid=
ence changes the best current understanding.

As such=2C science stands as a rare case for the uncomfortable luxury of c=
hanging one=E2=80=99s mind (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/23/nine-=
years-of-brain-pickings/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) amid a cu=
lture whose chief social currency is the artificial certitude of fixed opi=
nions (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/06/24/malcolm-gladwell-nypl-inte=
rview/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . The past century in parti=
cular =E2=80=94 a mere blink on the cosmological scale of time =E2=80=94 i=
s a supreme testament to this accelerating revision of accepted truth. Nat=
arajan writes:

In 1914=2C our own galaxy=2C the Milky Way=2C constituted the entire unive=
rse =E2=80=94 alone=2C stagnant=2C and small. Cosmological research still=
 relied fundamentally on classical conceptions of gravity developed in the=
 seventeenth century. Modern physics and the triumphs of general relativit=
y have shifted humanity=E2=80=99s entire comprehension of space and time.=
 Now we see the universe as a dynamic place=2C expanding at an acceleratin=
g rate=2C whose principal mysterious constituents=2C dark matter and dark=
 energy=2C are unseen. The remainder=2C all the elements in the periodic t=
able=2C the matter that constitutes stars and us=2C contributes a mere 4 p=
ercent of the total inventory of the universe.

Art by Bhajju Shyam from Creation (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/04/1=
5/creation-bhajju-shyam-gita-wolf-tara-books/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C an illustrated cosmogony of ancient Indian myths

Astrophysics=2C Natarajan notes=2C enlists the tools of science and reason=
 in investigating the same questions that our ancestors tried to answer th=
rough mythology:

Cosmology=2C perhaps more essentially than any other scientific discipline=
=2C has transformed not only our conception of the universe but also our p=
lace in it. This need to locate ourselves and explain natural phenomena se=
ems primordial. Ancient creation myths shared striking similarities across=
 cultures and helped humans deal with the uncertainty of violent natural p=
henomena. These supernatural explanations evoke a belief in an invisible a=
nd yet more powerful reality=2C and besides=2C they rely deeply on channel=
ing our sense of wonder at the natural world. The complex human imaginatio=
n enabled ancient civilizations to envision entities that were not immedia=
tely present but still felt real. Take for instance Enki=2C the Sumerian g=
od of water whose wrath unleashed floods=2C or the Hindu god of rain and t=
hunderstorms=2C Indra=2C whose bow was the rainbow stretched across the sk=
y with a lightning bolt as his arrow. The most powerful myths are the ones=
 that force us to take huge leaps of
imagination but=2C at the same time=2C help us to remain rooted.

Where science differs from mythology is that its findings are rooted into=
 culture through rigorous testing against observable reality rather than t=
hrough mere assertion. Natarajan writes:

The beauty of science is that while a theory is always provisional=2C it r=
epresents the best evidence and explanation that we have at any moment. Th=
ough prone to revision=2C science is based on replicable evidence=2C which=
 privileges scientific over all other possible explanations.

[=E2=80=A6]

Although science as a human endeavor is not entirely objective=2C it still=
 offers the best prescription for weighing evidence and making sense of th=
e natural world. Shifting and incomplete as it may be=2C science is self-c=
orrecting. It is the best method we have to navigate and make sense of thi=
s wondrous universe of ours. For centuries=2C science has helped us chart=
 our relationship to the natural world. And like any good map=2C it also p=
oints the way forward.

But although the path to answers is decidedly different=2C there is a prof=
ound parallel in the underlying objects of curiosity. Natarajan considers=
 her own formative bewitchment with the mystery of the cosmos and the invi=
sible thread by which it links her childhood in India=2C stargazing and tr=
ying to map the cosmos by programming a now-antique Commodore 64=2C to her=
 adult life as an astrophysicist doing cutting-edge research at some of th=
e world=E2=80=99s most renowned academic institutions:

At its heart=2C my research as a theoretical astrophysicist=2C mapping dar=
k matter and understanding the formation of black holes=2C is driven by th=
e same sense of wonder and search for explanation of the universe that the=
 ancients probably felt. I am still engaged in exploring the meanings of m=
aps and how they anchor us=2C matters that first intrigued me as a girl in=
 Delhi. My work exploits the bending of light from distant galaxies=2C gra=
vitational lensing=2C to map the invisible dark matter that causes these d=
eflections. I also investigate the formation and growth of the universe=E2=
=80=99s most bizarre and enigmatic objects=2C black holes.

An artist=E2=80=99s rendering of a black hole named Cygnus X-1=2C which fo=
rmed when a large star caved in and began pulling matter from blue star be=
side it. (Image: NASA/CXC/M.Weiss)

In fact=2C one of the most fascinating portions of the book explores the h=
istory of how the term =E2=80=9Cblack hole=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a term now a=
t the forefront of a new era of gravitational astronomy (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2016/04/25/black-hole-blues-janna-levin-joseph-weber/?mc_cid=
=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 came to be=2C from its dawn as=
 a metaphor for abomination and oblivion to its current use in science. Na=
tarajan maps the winding road of the lexicon:

It was not the peculiar properties of an astronomical object that first in=
spired the term =E2=80=9Cblack hole=E2=80=9D but rather a place =E2=80=94=
 an infamous prison. This was the scene of a gruesome incident on June 20=
=2C 1756. Sirajud-Daulah=2C the nawab=2C or ruler=2C of Bengal at that tim=
e=2C captured Calcutta from the East India Company=E2=80=99s troops=2C com=
manded by John Holwell=2C the self-proclaimed governor of Bengal. Upon sur=
render=2C the nawab confined Holwell and many other Europeans overnight in=
 the company=E2=80=99s own prison cell=2C a tiny=2C dark room=2C roughly s=
ix meters (twenty feet) long and four meters (thirteen feet) wide=2C with=
 two tiny windows=2C popularly known as =E2=80=9Cthe Black Hole.=E2=80=9D=
 Records of the incident from East India Company officials claim that 146=
 people were locked up in this minuscule cell=2C without adequate water an=
d in extreme heat=2C and that only twenty-three survived. Although scholar=
s such as J. H. Little have called these numbers into question=2C the Blac=
k Hole of Calcutta remains a powerful=2C
macabre reminder of and sordid metaphor for the utter callousness of the n=
awab. Soon =E2=80=9CBlack Hole of Calcutta=E2=80=9D entered the collective=
 consciousness as a synonym for the most horrific of experiences. When a r=
aging fire destroyed the Op=C3=A9ra comique building in Paris on May 25=2C=
 1887=2C a New York Times correspondent=2C noting that the seats=2C boxes=
=2C and balcony were gone=2C described the building as =E2=80=9Can immense=
 black hole.=E2=80=9D

1807 drawing of The Black Hole of Calcutta by James Cundee

Predating its adoption by physics=2C the phrase =E2=80=9Cblack hole=E2=80=
=9D has a long literary history of denoting a dark dungeon. As early as 18=
44=2C Edgar Allan Poe used it in his short story The Premature Burial and=
 as recently as 1997=2C Thomas Pynchon referred to the Black Hole of Calcu=
tta in his postmodernist novel Mason & Dixon. Its use in science can be tr=
aced back to the influential physicist John Archibald Wheeler=2C who popul=
arized it but didn=E2=80=99t originate it =E2=80=94 the originator=2C as i=
s often the case with linguistic invention=2C was an ordinary person whom=
 history has rendered anonymous. In her enchanting book Black Hole Blues (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/25/black-hole-blues-janna-levin-jose=
ph-weber/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C astrophysicist Janna=
 Levin relays the origin story: Weary of using the tedious =E2=80=9Ccomple=
tely collapsed gravitational object=2C=E2=80=9D Wheeler hungered for a mor=
e concise term; during a lecture he delivered in 1967=2C an audience membe=
r shouted: =E2=80=9CHow about black hole?=E2=80=9D Wheeler took to the phr=
ase
and went on to insert it into lectures and papers until it became the domi=
nant vocabulary.

Natarajan notes the inadvertent perfection of this spontaneously generated=
 term:

What is perhaps most surprising is just how well some of these description=
s fit an astrophysical object that had not yet been observed. In astronomy=
=2C a black hole is a physical location of no return.

Natarajan traces the route of this astrophysically perfect term from the g=
rim and gritty prisons of Calcutta to the ivory towers of Cambridge=2C Eng=
land:

In 1783=2C when an English country parson=2C John Michell=2C first propose=
d the idea of a =E2=80=9Cdark star=2C=E2=80=9D he could never have imagine=
d that we would one day detect them. Michell=2C a polymath born in 1724=2C=
 studied at Cambridge and later taught Hebrew=2C Greek=2C mathematics=2C a=
nd geology there. Although no portraits of him exist=2C a contemporary des=
cribed him as =E2=80=9Ca little short man=2C of black complexion=2C and fa=
t.=E2=80=9D A man of the cloth=2C he moved from Cambridge to a parish in T=
hornhill=2C near Leeds. Despite his religious commitments and duties=2C he=
 was very much at the leading edge of science=2C and his reputation for or=
iginality was such that many of the active scientists of the day=2C the li=
kes of Benjamin Franklin and Henry Cavendish=2C visited and maintained reg=
ular correspondence with him. They had much to discuss; Michell=E2=80=99s=
 scientific contributions include describing the strength of magnetic fiel=
ds and developing a theory for how earthquakes propagate through faults on=
 the earth=E2=80=99s surface.

[=E2=80=A6]

In a letter to Henry Cavendish dated November 27=2C 1783=2C Michell antici=
pated that such =E2=80=9Cdark stars=E2=80=9D would be observable only by t=
he impact they had on bodies revolving around them.

But as Newton=E2=80=99s particle theory of light (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2016/02/16/newton-standing-on-the-shoulders-of-giants/?mc_cid=3D834d=
946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) fell out of favor=2C Michell=E2=80=99s concept=
 of dark stars no longer made sense. It would be another century and a hal=
f until Einstein=E2=80=99s theory of general relativity made room within t=
he canon of scientific understanding for the possibility of such nonlumino=
us astronomical objects.

Natarajan considers the presently indispensable role of black holes in the=
 unfolding cosmic puzzle and puzzlement of our understanding:

Today we know that black holes exist in the centers of most=2C if not all=
=2C galaxies. Our own galaxy=2C the Milky Way=2C harbors one such black ho=
le four million times the mass of our sun=E2=80=A6 Fortunately=2C our sola=
r system is way too far from the center of the Milky Way for us to feel th=
e presence of or be affected by its central black hole.

Astronomers now believe that black holes=2C despite their odd behaviors=2C=
 are an inevitable consequence of the standard physics that describes the=
 evolution of stars. The theory of stellar evolution predicts that stars b=
orn fifteen to twenty times more massive than our sun=2C after exhausting=
 their fuel supply of hydrogen=2C will end their lives as black holes. Bla=
ck holes may have exotic properties=2C but they are important constituents=
 of the universe=2C playing a significant role in the assembly and evoluti=
on of galaxies.

This nonlinear and bumpy path from ideation to acceptance=2C Natarajan arg=
ues=2C is emblematic of how major scientific discoveries tend to progress=
 and how the grand human sensemaking journey unfolds:

We are living in a disorienting universe=2C whose expansion is acceleratin=
g. And at no other period in human history have we had to contend head on=
 so frequently with the provisionality of our understanding. We have a cos=
mic map that is eternally in flux. The fact that by their nature scientifi=
c truths are subject to refinement and revision is now an inescapable part=
 of our reality. Our world view has shifted sharply in the past hundred ye=
ars=2C rewriting the very sense of who we are=2C where we came from=2C and=
 where we are headed.

Complement Natarajan=E2=80=99s stimulating Mapping the Heavens (http://www=
=2Eamazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0300204418/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) with cosmologist Janna Levin=E2=80=99s poetic history of LIG=
O and gravitational astronomy (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/25/bl=
ack-hole-blues-janna-levin-joseph-weber/?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) =2C physicist Sean Carroll on the universe and our search for meani=
ng (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/31/sean-carroll-the-big-picture/=
?mc_cid=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and photographer Michael Bens=
on=E2=80=99s visual history of four millennia of picturing the cosmos (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/31/cosmigraphics-michael-benson/?mc_cid=
=3D834d946e6f&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


