0%;outline: none;text-decoration: none;padding: 5px 30px 10px 0px;display:=
 inline;width: 50px!important;">Only through [such] pure contemplation=
 =E2=80=A6 can Ideas be comprehended; and the nature of <em>genius</em> co=
nsists in pre-eminent capacity for such contemplation. Now=2C as this requ=
ires that a man* should entirely forget himself and the relations in which=
 he stands=2C <em>genius</em> is simply the completest <em>objectivity</em=
>=2C i.e.=2C the objective tendency of the mind=2C as opposed to the subje=
ctive=2C which is directed to one=E2=80=99s own self =E2=80=94 in other wo=
rds=2C to the will. Thus genius is the faculty of continuing in the state=
 of pure perception=2C of losing oneself in perception=2C and of enlisting=
 in this service the knowledge which originally existed only for the servi=
ce of the will; that is to say=2C genius is the power of leaving one=E2=80=
=99s own interests=2C wishes=2C and aims entirely out of sight=2C thus of=
