ena=2C and as the knowledge of the Idea is necessarily knowledge through p=
erception=2C is not abstract=2C the knowledge of the genius would be limit=
ed to the Ideas of the objects actually present to his person=2C and depen=
dent upon the chain of circumstances that brought these objects to him=2C=
 if his imagination did not extend his horizon far beyond the limits of hi=
s actual personal existence=2C and thus enable him to construct the whole=
 out of the little that comes into his own actual apperception=2C and so t=
o let almost all possible scenes of life pass before him in his own consci=
ousness=E2=80=A6 The imagination then extends the intellectual horizon of=
 the man of genius beyond the objects which actually present themselves to=
